<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Discusses Joining Two International Conventions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Delegates attending the ongoing
26th session of the Standing Committee of the Eighth National
People's Congress (NPC) here say that it is in China's best
interests to join an international convention on obtaining
evidence from overseas to be used in court cases involving civil
or business-related disputes, and to approve two items included in
a treaty on a nuclear-weapon-free zone in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has submitted a proposal on each issue to the
NPC for examination.
</P>
<P>
Delegates believe that the two proposals will help to promote
and strengthen China's cooperation with the international
community, and have suggested that the standing committee pass
them.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng said in one proposal that the convention on
obtaining evidence from overseas will have an important bearing on
international judicial cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
The convention is basically in line with China's legal and
judicial practices, the premier said, and joining the convention
will encourage broader cooperation between China and other
countries in the area of judicial aid.
</P>
<P>
Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs Li Zhaoxing, on behalf of the
State Council, pointed out in an explanation of the proposal that
China has always looked favorably on judicial cooperation when it
comes to obtaining evidence.
</P>
<P>
By September 1996, China had concluded treaties or agreements
with 23 countries for cooperation in obtaining evidence, either
for civil or business-related cases, from overseas.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that China cannot currently meet the demand of the
many countries requesting such evidence, because concluding a
treaty is complicated and time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's regulations on obtaining evidence are
relatively simple, while the convention has more detailed
rulings. Joining the convention will both tighten China's
cooperation with foreign countries and aid its opening-up and
economic growth, he pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Discusses Joining Two International Codes (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although some regulations of the convention concerning the
obtaining of evidence by consul and special envoy exceed the
criteria of China's legal regulations and judicial practice, they
will not be major obstacles to China's joining the convention, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
The treaty on a nuclear-weapon-free zone in Africa was passed
at the 31st summit meeting of the Organization of African Unity in
June, 1995 and opened for signing in Cairo in April, 1996. China
has signed the No.1 and No.2 protocols, Li said.
</P>
<P>
China has always respected and supported countries that
voluntarily decide to set up nuclear-weapon-free areas, in
accordance with the situation in the region, Li said in an
explanation of the proposal to approve the protocols.
</P>
<P>
China long ago pledged that it will not use or threaten to use
nuclear weapons against any non-nuclear weapon-bearing country or
region, and repeated the pledge in April, 1995 in a "national
statement" on the issue.
</P>
<P>
This has been China's consistent stand regarding
nuclear-weapon-free areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The themes and contents of the treaty and related protocols are
in line with China's stand on safeguarding world peace and
security, and preventing the proliferation of nuclear weapons, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
