<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Orphans on Increase in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Children orphaned by AIDS are the
largest and fastest growing group of children in "difficult
circumstances" in Zimbabwe, according to a latest report of the
U.N. Fund (UNICEF) available here today.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled "Children Living in a World With AIDS"
paints a gloomy picture of the world, saying by the end of 1996,
approximately eight percent of Zimbabwean children under 15 had
lost their mothers because of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS, the joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS,
estimates that by mid-1996, nine million children under 15
worldwide had lost their mothers to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of these children live in sub-Saharan
African countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Data provided by the U.S. Bureau of the Census and the World
Bank indicate that there are 1.2 million Ugandan children under
the age of 18 who have lost at least one parent to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS estimates that there are already over 23 million
people worldwide living with HIV, over 40 percent of whom are
women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
