<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Opens Mobile Phone Services in Red Sea Resort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Egypt opened today mobile phone
services in the Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh, nearly seven
months after Cairenes first flashed the device.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Transport and Communications Suleiman
Metwally announced that with the operation of the first mobile
phone service station in the area, two others will begin business
next month.
</P>
<P>
He said the three wireless service stations will be enough to
cover the booming resort, 600 kilometers south of the Egyptian
capital, to serve thousands of foreign tourists thronging there
every day to enjoy its sunshine and seashore.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that a project to link the entire Red Sea
with fiber-optic cables is already being implemented to increase
the efficiency of communications services in the area.
</P>
<P>
Egyptians first laid their hands on cellular phone last
November, just a few days before the convention of the third
Middle East and North African Economic Conference in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months since the portable phone service
was introduced into Greater Cairo (including Giza, Cairo and
Qaliubya), it has developed a notoriety for poor quality and hefty
costs.
</P>
<P>
Due to state monopoly over the mobile phone market, users have
to pay 1,700 to 4,000 Egyptian pounds (500 to 1,177 U.S. dollars)
for the gadget itself, 2,000 pounds (588 U.S. dollars) for
networking, as well as tolls 10 times more than those of ordinary
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
According to the Egyptian MENA news agency, a handful of cities
around Cairo, such as Alexandria, Ismalia and Port Said are
beginning to get access to the luxury recently. But southern
provinces and other far-flung areas are yet to wait out their
turn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
