<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crisis Between Israeli PM, FM Deepens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The crisis between Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Foreign Minister David Levy
deepened today as the latter canceled a scheduled meeting with
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was scheduled to meet Levy to work out a final
settlement of the crisis between them upon Levy's rage about his
exclusion from the government's decision-making process. This was
to be the third meeting between them in the past days aimed at
defusing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
But Levy informed Netanyahu only half an hour beforehand that
he would not show up for the meeting. Levy did so apparently out
of his anger over a secret meeting between National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
deputy Chairman Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The Sharon-Mazen meeting was held without the knowledge of the
foreign minister, and Netanyahu failed to inform Levy of the
meeting last week even when he tried to defuse the crisis between
them.
</P>
<P>
Levy is deeply worried about the possibility of Sharon's
takeover of his position in charge of the negotiations with the
Palestinians. Sources close to Levy said he insisted that
Netanyahu should make it clear that he, not Sharon, would be in
charge of the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has reportedly promised Levy during the previous two
meetings last week that Levy would not be left out again in the
decision-making process and would be in charge of the
Israeli-Palestinian talks. However, Levy began to doubt
Netanyahu's promises when the news of the Sharon-Mazen meeting
broke out.
</P>
<P>
Instead of meeting Netanyahu, Levy held consultations this
afternoon at the Foreign Ministry with other members from his
Gesher Party on the crisis. On his part, Netanyahu held a meeting
with Sharon in reaction to Levy's refusal to meet him.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said afterwards that he was interested in finding a
quick solution to his crisis with Levy. He also expressed full
confidence in the foreign minister despite the crisis, promising
that he would consult Levy on future government decisions.
</P>
<P>
It remained unclear if Netanyahu would announce the
long-delayed cabinet reshuffle on Monday as scheduled. Following
his acquittal by the High Court for his role in the Bar-On
scandal over the appointment of former Attorney General,
Netanyahu decided to reshuffle the cabinet to consolidate his
rule and clear the house.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle was also made possible following the resignation
of Finance Minister Dan Meridor, who was forced out of the
government because of his refusal to support Netanyahu during the
Bar-On affair.
</P>
<P>
Sharon met Mazen on June 16, immediately after he was offered
the finance portfolio. Sharon, a leading rightist hawk in the
cabinet, has since demanded to be included into the current
three-man inner cabinet which comprises of Netanyahu, Levy and
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
Levy is opposed to Sharon's inclusion into the inner cabinet,
warning that his hardline position could jeopardize the peace
process that has already been deadlocked in all tracks. Most
analysts predicted that Sharon's elevation in the government could
create more obstacles to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, Levy, together with four Gesher lawmakers,
deliberately absented himself from the crucial Knesset
(Parliament) no-confidence vote against Netanyahu to register his
anger. Levy even considered resignation to protest Netanyahu's
violation of commitments to consult him on important government
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Despite the depth of the Netanyahu-Levy crisis, analysts
believed that Levy still did not want to leave the coalition.
Like the first such crisis that occurred in last August, the two
traditional political rivals would hopefully work out a final
settlement over the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
