<HEADLINE> Jordan Lifts Restrictions on Foreign Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today formally lifted all
restrictions on foreign currency flow as part of the
government's efforts to attract foreign capital, Radio Jordan
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, Jordanian and foreign bank notes and
gold can enter and exit from the country freely, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The policy made by the Central Bank of Jordan (CBJ) in line
with the government's plan to liberalize foreign currency
transfer and further open up to the world market also lifted the
limitations on foreign currency withdrawal and transfer.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, there has been public fear here that
Jordan's foreign currency system was in danger as the government
imposed strict restrictions on foreign currency flow.
</P>
<P>
Under the restrictions, banks could not conduct foreign
currency transactions in a free way. A person was only allowed to
withdraw no more than 300 U.S. dollars once from his account, and
foreign currency interest rate was on decline.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's banks made huge profits from foreign currency
transfer for Iraq during the 1980s when altogether 18 European
and U.S. banks opened branches in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
