<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Ministers Denounce U.S. Decision on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Arab ministers of information today
termed as racist the recent U.S. congress' decision to transfer
the American embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem and to recognize
the holy city as the united capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Denouncing the decision, they said it is designed to Judaize
the city, regardless of the Palestinian claim of the eastern
sector of Jerusalem as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
"It gives the Israeli government a free hand in plundering more
Palestinian lands and encourages it to practice more intransigence
towards international resolutions," said the recommendations of
the 30th session of the Arab Information Ministers Council, which
concluded here today.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War and later
annexed it. But the annexation was not recognized by most
countries including the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The ministers called on the Arab media to unravel the dangers
of the congressional resolution and its repercussions on the Arab
and Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Adopting proposals agreed upon by the Arab League (AL) and the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC) with regard to Jerusalem,
the Council will prepare a pamphlet depicting Israeli violations
of human rights in Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also decided to coordinate between the AL and the
OIC to find a working mechanism for the UN General Assembly
decision at its extraordinary 10th session under the title
"Unity for the Sake of Peace" and to cooperate with UNESCO to
protect the historic heritage of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
They decided in the recommendations to promote Arab media and
culture in occupied lands to help Palestinian media face up to
existing challenges, and promote the establishment of the
Palestinian's Popular Liaison Institute.
</P>
<P>
Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdul Meguid in his speech
at the session said that the recommendations will give a strong
boost to Arab solidarity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
