<HEADLINE> Jordan, US Hold Military Cooperation Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian and U.S. senior military
officials held here today a meeting on military cooperation, Radio
Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Jordanian Chief of Staff of the Armed
Forces Abdul Hafiz Miree Kaabneh and the U.S. delegation led by
Air Force Commander in the U.S. Central Command Carl Franklin
reviewed the situation in the region, the Jordanian-U.S. relations in
military field and other issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Other details of the meeting have not been disclosed yet.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that the kingdom will receive the
first batch of altogether 16 F-16 jet fighters in December as
part of the 300 million U.S. dollars worth of military aid
pledged by the current U.S. administration.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, Egypt, Israel and Turkey are the only four countries
in the Middle East region that receive huge aid from the U.S. on
regular basis and maintain close military relations with
it.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and the U.S. have held two allied war games this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
