<HEADLINE> Bosnian-Croatian Summit Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A summit between Bosnian leader
Alija Izetbegovic and Croatian President Franjo Tudjman has been
postponed indefinitely due to a Muslim-Croat dispute on the
formation of joint police.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman's meeting with Izetbegovic, who is a Muslim and
chairman of the Bosnian Presidency, was originally scheduled to be
held in Split, Croatia, today.
</P>
<P>
According to Mirza Hajric, foreign advisor to Izetbegovic, the
main reason for the postponement was Bosnian Croats' refusal to
form the joint police in the Herzegovina-Neretva Canton in
proportion to the pre-war census.
</P>
<P>
The Croats have insisted on ethnic balance of the police force
in line with the current population of the region, which "would
result in hampering the return of refugees," Hajric told the local
press.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Croatian government criticized the Bosnian
Muslim side for the third postponement of the summit.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible to organize the meeting if there are any
conditions imposed, while the very aim of the meeting was supposed
to be the resolution of problems hampering the (Dayton)
agreements' implementation," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
