<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Homes Sales in US Up by 7.1 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- New home sales in the U.S. shot
up by 7.1 percent in May, rebounding from a big loss just a month
earlier, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that sales of single-family homes totaled a
seasonally adjusted 825,000 annual rate, up sharply from a revised
770,000 a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
New home sales in the U.S. hit 838,000 in March, the highest
since April 1986. But sales fell steeply by 8.1 percent in April
1997.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, sales of new homes were 9.4 percent above
those of the first five months of last year. During all of 1996,
757,000 new homes were sold in the country.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the seasonally adjusted estimate of new
homes for sale at the end of May was 280,000, lowest since 278,000
in July 1993. It represented a supply of 4.1 months at the current
sales rate, smallest since a four-month supply in March 1971.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, sales jumped by 23.9 percent in the Midwest, the
biggest gain since a 31.7 percent advance in January 1996. Sales
increased 15.1 percent in the Northeast and 5.3 percent in the
South. But they fell 4.4 percent in the West.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. National Association of Realtors also reported last
week that sales of existing homes jumped 4.4 percent in May to a
level just shy of the record set a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The association attributed the advance to homeowners desire to
trade up, which was supported by the highest level of consumer
confidence in 28 years and the lowest unemployment rate in a
quarter-century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
