<HEADLINE> Japanese Firms Optimistic About HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, JUNE 30 (Xinhua) -- Japan's private enterprises are
optimistic about Hong Kong's role as an international financial
center after its return to China on July 1, business leaders here
said today.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pretty sure that Hong Kong will continue to grow as an
international financial and trade center," said Minoru Murofushi,
president of Japan's major trading house Itochu Corp.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's continued prosperity will be vital to the progress
not only of the economy of Asia but also of the world economy,"
said Shoichiro Toyota, chairman of the Federation of Economic
Organizations (Keidanren).
</P>
<P>
Electric machinery makers, which account for about 40 percent
of Japanese manufacturers' investment in Hong Kong, remain
interested in Hong Kong as a target for their funds.
</P>
<P>
"We expect Hong Kong to maintain its regulation-free and
transparent society," Yoichi Morishita, president of Matsushita
Electric Industrial Co. said. His company intended to use Hong
Kong's financial and distribution functions.
</P>
<P>
With the Chinese government guaranteeing the maintenance of
Hong Kong's existing financial and monetary systems, Japan's
banking sector is upbeat about their activities there.
</P>
<P>
Naotaka Saeki, chief of the Federation of Bankers Associations
of Japan, welcomed Hong Kong's return to China at midnight Monday,
saying he hopes Hong Kong will prosper further as a global
financial center and strengthen ties with Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
