<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Handover Ceremony to Begin Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong handover ceremony
that has been attracting worldwide attention is to start soon on
level five of the Extension to the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center (HKCEC).
The ceremony is expected to last 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony will be delegations of the Chinese and
British governments led respectively by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and Prince Charles of Britain.
</P>
<P>
Close at midnight today, the Union Jack of Britain will be
lowered at the ceremony. At zero hour of July 1, a five-star red
flag will be raised here. This will be the first five-star red
flag to be raised in Hong Kong, signifying China's resumption of
the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong and the end of 156
years of British colonial rule here.
</P>
<P>
Present at today's ceremony will be more than 4,000 guests from
more than 40 countries and regions and more than 30 international
organizations, more than 300 representatives of overseas Chinese
and foreigners of Chinese origin in all parts of the world,
personages from Macao and Taiwan, and local Hong Kong figures.
Nearly 600 out of more than 8,000 Chinese and foreign reporters
are permitted to cover the historic event.
</P>
<P>
The rostrum in front of the viewing stand is covered with red
carpet, and two silver-colored flagpoles stand at each side of the
rostrum. The British national flag and the Hong Kong flag are
flying on the flagpoles on the right.
</P>
<P>
In the center of the rostrum, on raised daises, are ten wooden
chairs, where leading officials from China and Britain will be
seated.
</P>
<P>
The HKCEC is located at Wanchai on the northern side of Hong
Kong Island, overlooking the Kowloon Peninsula across the Victoria
Harbor.
</P>
<P>
The newly completed Extension to the HKCEC was constructed on
a 6.5-hectare man-made island. The Extension resembles a flying
seabird in shape, symbolizing Hong Kong's economic takeoff to even
greater prosperity. The entire center has more than 63,000 square
meters in floor space for convention and exhibition alone. It is
one of the largest facilities of its kind in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The venue of the handover ceremony--the Grand Hall and the Grand
Foyer on level five of the Extension -- has a combined floor space
of more than 6,000 square meters, the size of a football field.
On the giant glass wall overlooking the sea hang the national
flags of China and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The handover ceremony will be televised live to every corner of
the world via satellites. Billions of people across the world are
expected to witness the solemn event on TV screens.
</P>
<P>
The HKCEC is now the focus of world attention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harbor Plaza Hotel Wins Double Honor Before Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Shortly before the handover
ceremony begins, Harbor Plaza Hotel in Kowloon, a local five-star
hotel, has won a double honor.
</P>
<P>
The hotel, which belongs to Hong Kong tycoon Li Ka-shing, has
been chosen as the residence for the Chinese government delegation
headed by President Jiang Zemin to attend the handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Members of the delegation, which arrived here by special plane
this afternoon, include Premier Li Peng and other senior
officials.
</P>
<P>
Harbor Plaza Hotel has thus become the first local hotel to
accommodate top Chinese leaders, who have for the first time set
foot on this part of Chinese soil.
</P>
<P>
The hotel has also become the venue for a meeting between
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng, and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair this evening, thus witnessing the first
meeting between Chinese and British leaders in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With 415 rooms, Harbor Plaza Hotel is located by the
picturesque Victoria Harbor, and opposite the Hong Kong Convention
and Exhibition Center (HKCEC), the venue for the handover
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
It takes only a dozen minutes to reach the HKCEC from the hotel
dock by boat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
