<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Expresses Full Confidence in Hong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official
expressed here today full confidence in Hong Kong's future of
continuing to be democratic and prosperous.
</P>
<P>
Eitan Ben-Tsur, Director-General of Israeli Foreign Ministry,
made the comments at the signing ceremony of an agreement with
Chinese Ambassador Wang Changyi on mutual exemption of visa
requirements between Hong Kong and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Both sides said the signing of the agreement on exemption of
visa requirements would certainly help promote the already good
trade relations between Israel and China.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the ever-improving bilateral ties, Ben-Tsur told Wang
that Israel trusted Beijing to preserve the well-being and
prosperity of Hong Kong after its return to China.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel has full confidence that democracy and
prosperity will prevail in Hong Kong after the historic handover
at midnight tonight.
</P>
<P>
Wang Changyi said the basic principle of Chinese government's
policies regarding Hong Kong is "one country, two systems,"
which is aimed at ensuring the long-term prosperity and
stability of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Noting Israel has already been an important trade partner of
Hong Kong and China, Wang expressed the hope that Sino-Israeli
trade and economic relations would further develop after the
handover.
</P>
<P>
In answering question by an Israel radio reporter, Ben-Tsur
said that Israel would not monitor the so-called democracy
situation in Hong Kong since it trusts China.
</P>
<P>
"We have good and close relations with China, and we will
discuss whatever items that will come up," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
