<HEADLINE> Weizman Apologizes for Anti-Muslim Posters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman today
apologized to the Muslim world in the wake of the distribution of
an anti-Islamic leaflet in the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release faxed to Xinhua by the Israeli
Embassy in Cairo, Weizman characterized in his apology the posters
depicting the Muslim Prophet Mohammad as a pig stomping on the
Koran as "despicable and insulting."
</P>
<P>
He regretted that the single incident could sour Muslim-Jewish
ties and add fuel to the all-time tense situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Tremendous damage had been caused by the stupidity of a single
individual," the release quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Muslim hate posters glued to about 20 Arab storefronts
near a Jewish settlement overnight Saturday have sparked two days
of renewed violence in the divided West Bank city. Israeli police
said a 25-year-old Jewish woman from Jerusalem had pasted the
leaflets.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu also expressed his
"revulsion" against such an offending act.
</P>
<P>
"This runs counter to our outlook as Jews and our respect and
appreciation for the Islamic religion and for its founder the
Prophet Mohammad," he told Jewish leaders at a conference in
Jerusalem Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Violence and provocations have been rife in the occupied
territories as international mediation has failed to resuscitate
the deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace talks that collapsed in
March over the construction of a new Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
