<HEADLINE> Arafat Vows to Regain Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat today reiterated his determination to
take Jerusalem as the capital of a future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem is the key to Middle East and is the capital of the
independent Palestine," said Arafat in a speech addressed to a
ceremony here marking the Solidarity Day With Jerusalem today.
</P>
<P>
The speech was delivered by Mohamed Sobeih, PNA's chief
delegate to the Cairo-based Arab League.
</P>
<P>
Arafat accused the Israeli government of Binjamin Netanyahu of
pursuing a settlement policy, particularly in Jerusalem, to
undermine the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem, Muslim's third holiest city, is a kingpin of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, which bogged down in March over
the construction of a new Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians claim as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast war and annexed
it later. But the annexation was not recognized by most nations,
including the U.S..
</P>
<P>
He said the much-condemned Jabal Abu Ghneim settlement, also
known as Har Homa, is only one aspect of the comprehensive Jewish
settlement scheme meant to isolate Jerusalem from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader described the U.S. House of
Representatives' resolution to transfer the U.S. Embassy from Tel
Aviv to Jerusalem as a reward to Netanyahu for his anti-peace
plans.
</P>
<P>
His remarks followed recent uproar over the U.S. congress'
decision to recognize the holy city as the united capital of
Israel. The U.S. government, a key sponsor of the Mideast peace,
later reaffirmed its stance on settling the Jerusalem issue in
Palestinian-Israeli final talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
