<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Kenya Top Tourism Revenue in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa topped the tourism
revenue charts for Africa last year with 1.74 billion U.S.
Dollars while Kenya being the second with 493 million and
Tanzania the third with 322 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were 4,640,000 tourists to South Africa and
728,000 to Kenya, compared with 326,000 to Tanzania and 214,000
to Uganda, according to the latest report from the World Tourism
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
However, Uganda now leads eastern Africa in the tourism growth
rate and Tanzania is way ahead in terms of increased revenue from
tourist receipts. Kenya still has the highest number of arrivals
and bed occupancy in the region.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals in Uganda rose by 13.2 percent in the
1995-1996 fiscal year but the country's gains from tourist
receipts went up by only 3.8 percent, said the WTO report.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania saw a 10.5 percent increase in tourist arrivals and
24.3 percent rise in receipts, while Kenya registered hikes of
just 5.4 percent in arrivals and 8.6 percent in receipts.
</P>
<P>
The average spending per tourist in Tanzania hit the
988-Dollar mark last year, up from 595 Dollars in 1992, said the
report. The figure stood at 677 Dollars in Kenya, 383 Dollars in
Uganda and 374 Dollars in South Africa in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
