<HEADLINE> Britain Holds Farewell Ceremony in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 -- The Union Jack was lowered at 7:45 p.m.
local time in a farewell ceremony held by the British at the East
Tamar site today, marking the end of more than 150 years of
Britain's colonial rule over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The farewell ceremony, known as the "sunset ceremony," was
attended by the British heir-to-the-throne Prince Charles, Prime
Minister Tony Blair and Governor of Hong Kong Chris Patten. It was
held at the East Tamar site not far from the British armed force
headquarters in the Prince of Wales Barracks.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a message of the British Queen at the ceremony,
Prince Charles said that the eyes of the world are on Hong Kong
today.
</P>
<P>
"Five hours from now the Union Flag will be lowered and the
flag of China will fly over Hong Kong. More than a century and a
half of British administration will come to an end," the prince
read.
</P>
<P>
He added, "we have no doubt that Hong Kong people can run Hong
Kong, as the Joint Declaration promises."
</P>
<P>
Prior to the official farewell ceremony, Governor Chris Patten
bid farewell to the Government House in Central District, where he
had lived for the past five years, in a ceremony to lower the
Governor's standard and its presentation to Patten. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
