<HEADLINE> Northernmost City Greets Hong Kong's Return with Bonfires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOHE, HEILONGJIANG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- People of China's
northernmost county of Mohe built bonfires along the Heilongjiang
River, located along the border between China and Russia, to mark
the historical moment when China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty in Hong Kong at midnight tonight.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three days, more than 3,000 people have gathered
under the stone tablet which bears the inscription "Northernmost
Point of China," and are throwing bonfire parties along the river.
</P>
<P>
The event was also attended by tourists and soldiers stationed
there, who sang along with local residents and performed martial
arts and ethnic dances.
</P>
<P>
Though daytime is longer in the county because of its high
altitude, people ended their celebrations parties before dusk to
catch the Hong Kong handover ceremony that will be broadcast live
through the night by the China Central TV station.
</P>
<P>
At Mohe Meteorological Station, the northernmost meteorological
observatory in the country, director Feng Xianhua said that though
Mohe is thousands of miles away from Hong Kong, he will visit
China's economic powerhouse if he gets the chance.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow morning, a new national flag will be raised near the
boundary river at the same time the flag-raising ceremony is held
in Tian'anmen Square. Xu Hongshui, head of Mohe Township in the
county, said that every Chinese person is obliged to safeguard the
country's territory as well as its ongoing economic
take-off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
