<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands in Sydney, Melbourne Celebrate HK Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people gathered
tonight at the heart of Sydney and Melbourne, the two largest
cities of Australia, to celebrate China's resumption of its
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, hundreds of Australian-Chinese gathered at the heart
of the city's Chinatown as the clock was ticking away the hours
before the handover of Hong Kong to China at midnight on June 30.
</P>
<P>
People in the Market City shopping center complex in Haymarket
were in a festive mood for the historic occasion, enjoying
entertainment which included performances by Hong Kong-born
singers.
</P>
<P>
Scenes of the handover at midnight Hong Kong time will be
beamed live onto a large screen by courtesy of SBS TV, a local
television station.
</P>
<P>
Shops and restaurants at Chinatown brimmed with patrons taking
advantage of their extended trading hours until 2 AM.
</P>
<P>
Wong, 35, who was born in Hong Kong and made Sydney his home 16
years ago, said the handover will mark the beginning of a new era
for the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"From tonight onwards, we will be able to identify ourselves as
Chinese. For me, it's like finding the lost part of myself," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Teresa Cheng, 40, who was also born in Hong Kong and has been
living in Sydney for 20 years, is the managing director of the
Chinatown Promotions and Public Relations company which helped
organize tonight's celebrations with Market City management.
</P>
<P>
"It is a happy event for us ..." she said. "Hong Kong always
belongs to China and I am confident things will be okay."
</P>
<P>
One of the youngest taking part in tonight's celebrations was
13-year-old Andy Yung, who was born in Hong Kong and came to
Sydney five years ago. His sister, Eva, 19, said: "It is now a day
for history and celebration."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at a party billed as Australia's largest changeover
party, more than 1,300 guests in Melbourne tonight prepared to
mark China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations, which began this evening at Melbourne's Crown
Casino, will continue until early tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
In Melbourne's Chinatown, along Little Bourke street, thousands
were expected to gather at a series of functions held to mark the
end of British colonial rule in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Restaurants have set up large screens for diners to watch
ceremonies in Hong Kong, but none could match the size of the
casino celebration organized by the Victorian Chinese Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Entertainment at the casino ranged from Scottish bagpipers to
traditional lion dances, acrobatic displays, and performances by
Normie Rowe and Hong Kong entertainer Susie Shen.
</P>
<P>
An indoor fireworks display was planned for the celebration's
climax.
</P>
<P>
Chamber spokesman Norman Wong said the 1,400 guests at the
casino would comprise the largest single celebration of the
changeover planned for Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Editorial: Let's Celebrate HK's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- "Let's celebrate Hong Kong's return
to China tonight," the newspaper Macao Daily News said in an
editorial today.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will become the global spotlight tonight, not only
because Britain will end its 150-year-plus colonial rule in the
Far East, but also because China has set an example in peacefully
handling disputes left over from the past, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is to start a new historical era," said the
editorial. "Everywhere across the world, so long as there are
Chinese, there will be celebrations and joy."
</P>
<P>
China has won respect from the righteous nations around the
world in its peaceful resumption of exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The Si Man Pou newspaper said in a commentary that Hong Kong's
return to the embrace of the motherland is the common wish of the
six-million-strong Hong Kong citizens and also the long-cherished
wish of the 1.2 billion Chinese people as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"Now that the long-awaited moment is coming, how can we keep
ourselves from being excited and happy?" said the commentary. "We
should carry on the will of Deng Xiaoping and make Hong Kong and
Macao more prosperous."
</P>
<P>
Another commentary in today's Sing Pou newspaper said July 1
will be the most glorious day in the history of the Chinese
nation, because Hong Kong's return to the motherland is "like a
son returning to his family after more than 150 years of
separation."
</P>
<P>
"It is the most encouraging and most exciting moment," said the
commentary. "People in Hong Kong and Macao will have a joyful
night tonight."
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, Macao is to hold two grand parties tonight
to mark the historic moment. Thousands of Macao residents will
dance and sing throughout the night and will also count down to
the moment of handover. The local television station will
broadcast live the handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a fireworks show will start at midnight.
</P>
<P>
Some commentaries urged the Macao government to quicken its
pace in the localization of the civil service, the localization of
law and the use of Chinese as an official language so that
Macao's handover will be conducted smoothly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
