<HEADLINE> Israeli Taxation Policy in Jerusalem Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian government and
Islamic figures have strongly condemned Israeli taxation policy in
East Jerusalem, according to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian
press service based in the city, today.
</P>
<P>
Suleiman al-Najab, member of the Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) Executive Committee and one of the leaders of
the Palestinian People's Party, said that it seems that the policy
of the Israeli government intends to liquidate all kinds of our
people's presence in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Al-Najab was commenting on Israeli decision to adopt measures
against Palestinians evading taxes in East Jerusalem. On Sunday,
Palestinian merchants in East Jerusalem went on a strike
demanding that the Israeli authorities cancel a 286
million-U.S.-dollar debt owed by the merchants in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of shopkeepers marched from the city center to the
Damascus Gate of the Old City and demonstrated for several hours,
with placards reading "Stop raiding our homes and shops," and
"Israeli taxation means only transfer."
</P>
<P>
The protesters told reporters that the Israeli policy --
including closure of the West Bank and military presence in the
Old City -- have reduced revenues and scared away customers,
making it impossible for the shopkeepers to pay their debts.
</P>
<P>
Al-Najab said bitterly that in its policy the Israeli
government finds no support country except the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Jamil Othman Nasser, the Palestinian National
Authority-appointed governor of Jerusalem, said that all the
Israeli measures in Jerusalem are aimed at forcing the Palestinian
residents to leave the city, so that when the final status
negotiations begin the Palestinian side will find nothing to talk
about.
</P>
<P>
He noted that all of the Palestinians insist in their rights
in Jerusalem, adding that "without Jerusalem, there will be no
negotiations, no state and no co-existence."
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud al-Zahar, one of the leaders of the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas), said that "arguments (by Israel) about the
eternal capital of Israel are historic lies which cannot be
accepted by the Muslims anyway." 
</P>
</TEXT>
