<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiananmen Square Ready For Celebrating HK's Homecoming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Tian'anmen Square has been
turned into a sea of jubilant people, numbering more than 100,000;
colored flags are flying in the balmy summer air; and numerous
traditional Chinese red lanterns are hanging over and around the
Square, where an all-night gala party is ready to begin in
celebration of the long-waited homecoming of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At 8:00 p.m., 60 minutes ahead of the scheduled gala, when the
giant countdown board displayed the words, "It is 13,500 seconds
before the Chinese government resumes the exercise of sovereignty
over Hong Kong," the square was resounded with thunderous beating
of drums and gongs.
</P>
<P>
In the final hours before the big event, many people were
elbowing through the crowd to take pictures in front of the clock.
</P>
<P>
Tonight, the world's largest square is ablaze with floodlights;
red lanterns are hung on the Tiananmen Rostrum, the Great Hall of
the People, the Museum of the Chinese Revolution, the Museum of
Chinese History, and the Memorial Hall of Chairman Mao and along
the Chang'an Avenue, the major thoroughfare that runs across the
city proper.
</P>
<P>
Six huge lighted boxes, positioned at the center of the square,
bear the six giant Chinese characters which mean "Celebrating the
Return of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Two stages have been erected on the square: a central stage,
covered with red carpet, just in front of the countdown board, and
a double-decker platform, 35 meters in both length and width, at
the square's center. A variety of performances will take place
there.
</P>
<P>
The celebration activities, scheduled to begin at 10 p.m., will
last until 5:05 a.m. on July 1. Five TV screens on the square will
display the live broadcast of the handover ceremony in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong is an event I've long been looking
forward to, and I will never forget this historical night here,"
said Beijing resident Jin Xiaoyao.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 Chinese and overseas reporters are on the square to
cover the event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
