<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Approves New Cabinet List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkey President Suleyman Demirel
has approved the new government led by Motherland Party (ANAP)
leader Mesut Yimaz.
</P>
<P>
Yimaz made the announcement at the presidential palace at noon
after Demirel held a one-hour-long meeting with him for the
approval of the coalition government consisting of the ANAP,
Democratic Left Party (DSP), and Democratic Turkey Party (DTP).
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz told reporters that he believed that the
newly-established government would overcome the current
difficulties with the support of the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
The formation of Turkey's 55th government has started to help
ease the political tension in Turkey, said the new prime minister,
adding that this situation has given hope to the whole country.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz submitted the cabinet list to Demirel for approval
following extensive talks with his coalition partners this morning.
</P>
<P>
He said that DSP leader Bulent Ecevit, also former prime
minister, became deputy prime minister and DTP deputy chairman and
former parliamentary speaker Ismet Sezgin now serves as deputy
prime minister and national defense minister.
</P>
<P>
According to the cabinet list, ANAP member Murat Basesgioglu
took the interior minister's portfolio and DSP members Ismail Cem
and Zekeriya Temizel respectively serve as foreign minister and
financial minister.
</P>
<P>
The Yilmaz government will obtain a vote of confidence within
two weeks at the lastest.
</P>
<P>
As of Sunday, the Motherland Party-led alliance enjoys 278
votes in the 550-seat parliament with a vacancy of two, and an
alliance of the Welfare Party (RP) and the True Path Party (DYP),
with BBP and three independents support, has 270 seats in the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that at present Yilmaz and his alliance
would have no difficulty in winning a vote of confidence in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Yilmaz government is expected to assume assignment on
Tuesday from the caretaker government led by Necmettin Erbakan,
who resigned on June 18.
</P>
<P>
Among the priorities of the new government is to reopen the
corruption files concerning Deputy Prime Minister and DYP Leader
Tansu Ciller which was blocked time and again by senior coalition
partner RP.
</P>
<P>
Local English newspaper Daily News said that this move was
aimed at wiping out Ciller from the Turkish political arena.
</P>
<P>
Ciller's efforts to gain the premiership from her coalition
partner Erbakan are bound to failure when her deputies resigned
one after another.
</P>
<P>
On June 20, Demirel assigned Yilmaz to form a new government to
replace the resigned RP-DYP coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, who had planned to taker over premiership from Erbakan,
was annoyed by Demirel's appointment of Yilmaz to form a new
government, calling it "a Cankaya (presidential palace) coup."
</P>
<P>
She has said that the RP-DYP alliance with the support of
the nationalist BBP could defeat Yilmaz's efforts to set up a
new government in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, however, expressed optimism about the new government,
saying that he believed the new government would win a vote of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the developments in the coming days will
expand the margin. The outcome of the vote will not be very
close," the ANAP leader said.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan stepped down under pressure from both the military and
DYP deputies, who have repeatedly criticized the Islamic RP
ledaer for his reluctance to curb rapidly expanding
fundamentalists force in the secular Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
