<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Needs More Efforts to Expand Non-oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has to make still greater
efforts to boost its export of non-oil products as the
performance in this regard "remained unimpressive" last year,
according to a Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) report.
</P>
<P>
Although the country's aggregate exports jumped from 11.734
billion U.S. dollars in 1995 to 16.12 billion in 1996, non-oil
exports only grew marginally from 285.7 million to 287.2 million,
revealed the CBN annual report and statement of accounts for
1996.
</P>
<P>
The CBN attributed the slight increase in non-oil exports to
the depressed prices of palm produce and cocoa in the
international market. Other non-oil products for export mainly
include minerals.
</P>
<P>
According to the central bank, Nigeria exported 745.9 million
barrels of crude oil last year, up from 666 million barrels
recorded in the previous year. The average price also increased
to 21.21 dollars per barrel from 17.33 dollars correspondingly.
</P>
<P>
Oil exports in 1996 accounted for 98.2 percent of the
country's total exports while the share of non-oil exports stood
at less than two percent.
</P>
<P>
This indicated that although the Nigerian government has vowed
to expand non-oil exports in a bid to diversify the channel of
foreign exchange income, the country still heavily depends on oil
exports.
</P>
<P>
While non-oil exports dropped, non-oil imports also went down
substantially last year, from an all time high of 601.64 billion
naira (about 7.08 billion dollars at current exchange rate) in
1995 to 400.98 billion naira (about 4.7 billion dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The CBN attributed this development to continued restriction
of import financing of letter of credit as well as delays arising
from administrative changes for clearing goods at the ports which
required all imports to be accompanied by import duty reports.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of imports by end users however showed that the
share of consumer goods in total imports increased by 5.6 percent
to 38.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, capital goods and raw material imports as a group
fell from 66.8 percent in 1995 to 61 percent last year. This,
according to observers, paints a negative picture of the
industrial sector which depends on capital goods and raw
materials to increase production.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured goods continued to rank highest in non-oil
imports. In 1996, it peaked at 158.27 billion naira (about 1.86
billion dollars) or 28.1 percent of the total imports, while
chemicals valued at 134.05 billion naira (about 1.58 billion
dollars) or 23.8 percent were recorded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
