<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq: Syria Is Not Prepared to Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi official has said
that Syria is not prepared to resume its relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi minister of culture and information Hamed Youssef Hammadi
made the remarks in an interview Sunday with the Jordanian
newspaper al-Arab Today in Amman, capital of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) quoted Hammadi as saying that Iraq
and Syria have been seeking, over the past years, to resume
bilateral relations. However, the Syrians were not prepared to do
so.
</P>
<P>
He said that Syrian businessmen "betrayed" recently their
desire to re-export to Iraq foodstuffs and medicines under the
Iraqi-U.N. "oil-for-food" deal, which allows Iraq to sell oil to
raise money to buy food and other necessities for humanitarian
needs in the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq signed last month several contracts with Syrian companies
to import food and other daily necessities under the deal.
</P>
<P>
It also declared that its customs offices on the border with
Syria will soon be reopened and it has asked for the U.N.
permission to open a crossing on the Iraq-Syria border for
transporting humanitarian goods bought by Baghdad under the
"oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
<P>
Recent developments showed that the relations between Baghdad
and Damascus have begun to thaw after a Syrian trade and
industrial delegation visited Iraq, the first of its kind in the
past 17 years, and an Iraqi trade delegation paid a return visit.
</P>
<P>
However, observers here noted that there is a long way to go
for the two long-time rivals before their relations are
normalized.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad severed its diplomatic ties with Damascus in 1980
following the eight-year Iraqi-Iranian War broke out, because
Syria sided with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations worsened farther after the Syrian
troops joined in the U.S.-led allied forces to drive Iraqi
troops out of Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President, Premier to Meet with Blair in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and Premier Li Peng are due to meet with British Prime Minister
Tony Blair here this evening.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, scheduled to begin at 8 p.m. in the Harbor Plaza
Hotel at Hung Hom, Kowloon, will be the first one for top Chinese
and British leaders in Hong Kong, and also the first rendezvous
between the heads of government of China and Britain since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook are expected to be present at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng arrived here by
special plane at around five o'clock this afternoon to attend the
Hong Kong handover ceremony at midnight today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that top Chinese leaders have set foot
on this part of Chinese soil, which was under the British colonial
rule over the past one and a half centuries.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair flew into here earlier today.
</P>
</TEXT>
