<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President Leaves for Athens for Talks on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides left here today for Athens of Greece on a three-day
visit for talks on the protracted Cyprus question with the Greek
government in view of the forthcoming direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before his departure, Clerides said that he had to
visit Athens in order to coordinate and discuss with the Greek
government issues on the strategy of handling the Cyprus question,
in view of the fact that Greece will be in the wings of the
U.N.-led direct talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the Athens talks, "we will not discuss any
changes of our positions," agreed between the two governments in
the past both in Nicosia and Athens.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the ongoing military dialog between the Greek
Cypriot National Guard and the Turkish forces to discuss the
U.N. proposal aimed at reducing tension on the island, Clerides
said he does not think an agreement on the military dialog is
possible before his face-to-face talks with Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Clerides' trip to Athens came just a week before the
U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations between leaders of the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities are to take place from
July 9 to 13 near New York.
</P>
<P>
The talks are aimed at hammering out a comprehensive solution
to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took control
of the northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
