<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Maintains Alert in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine troops have been
maintaining red alert status in Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, to prevent any retaliatory attacks by Muslim rebels
who fought fierce battles with soldiers last week, the military
said today.
</P>
<P>
Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the Army's Sixth Infantry Division,
said Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels might launch
retaliatory attacks against government forces who overran an MILF
camp in Pikit Town, North Cotabato Province, last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said latest intelligence reports monitored movements of big
groups of MILF rebels circling the remote areas near Pikit in what
has been perceived as an attempt to take back the camp.
</P>
<P>
The government forces are now busy securing the entire area for
the thousands of evacuees affected by the recent conflict that
killed about 100 rebels, soldiers and civilians, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 40,000 residents fled the conflict, the fiercest so far
this year, and sought refuge in various evacuation centers,
earlier reports said.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos has released an initial 3 million pesos
(114,000 U.S. dollars) as relief funds for the conflict-affected
areas in the provinces of North Cotabato and Maguindanao.
</P>
</TEXT>
