<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Chair ASEAN Standing Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will chair the
Standing Committee of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) and the ASEAN Regional Forum starting in July, the
official Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Manila welcomes these tasks assigned to the country by the
collective ASEAN leadership, the report quoted officials at the
Foreign Department as saying.
</P>
<P>
The chairmanship of the Philippines becomes all the more
challenging because of the ASEAN's membership expansion with the
admission of Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar next month, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Part of the committee chairmanship responsibility is the close
monitoring of the three new member countries' adherence to and
performance of their membership obligations in the ASEAN and
helping them adjust to the demands of their membership in the
regional bloc.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Standing Committee, which reports directly to the
ASEAN Ministerial Meeting, is the policy-making and coordinating
organ of the regional bloc.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN, which now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, will finally realize
its ASEAN-10 vision with the formal admission of Cambodia, Laos
and Myanmar in July.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Regional Forum is a consultative forum between the
group and its dialogue partners including China, Japan, New
Zealand, Australia, Russia, the United States and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
The forum meets yearly immediately after the annual ASEAN
Ministerial Meeting to discuss security matters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan to Attract Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Kazakh government will
continue to place top priority on attracting foreign investments,
a government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Kazakhstan would attract 5.28 billion
U.S. dollars of foreign investment, including loans, credits and
direct foreign investment this year.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh government plans to attract 22 billion dollars from
1997-2000 between 1997 and 2000, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's investment environment has been improved and it
attracted 1.9 billion dollars of foreign investment last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman pointed out that some Kazakh enterprises
have suffered bad economic results and could not repay loans and
credit. As a result, it has brought some disadvantages to the
government's efforts to attract more foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Turkey, Germany and South Korea are
the main investors in Kazakhstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
