<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Strengthen Economic Structure for Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Acting Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today that the
country needs to strengthen its economic structure in order to
continue to achieve quality growth.
</P>
<P>
Strict controls would be imposed on government spending in the
1998 budget whose policy will stress prudent and disciplined
spending to avoid unnecessary spending and waste, he said at the
first session of the 1998 budget dialogue here.
</P>
<P>
He said the government expenditure must be according to
allocation and additional expenditure outside the allocated sum
would not be allowed except if they were approved by federal
agencies in urgent cases for health, education and rural
development programs.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of the dialogue whose theme is "Sustaining High
Quality Growth," the minister said that in addition, the country's
existing strong financial standing ought to be closely nurtured by
the regulatory financial authorities and that banks should have
prudent internal management.
</P>
<P>
"This is to prevent Malaysia from being affected by financial
crisis which had affected a few other countries recently as a
result of non-performing loans in view of the over-exposure of
their banking systems to the property sector and the poor quality
of loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has projected a growth of 8 percent for this year
after a growth of 8.8 percent for nine consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate for the first five months of this year
amounted to 2.9 percent compared with 3.5 percent last year and
the country's balance of payment for the first four months of this
year showed a small deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian economy has been described by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) as having achieved "high quality growth" which
has brought benefits to all segments of society while the rate of
poverty has been sharply reduced.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus cited
Malaysia as a model country in the efforts to sustain stable
economic growth while strengthening its strong banking system,
according to Anwar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Share prices rose on the
Singapore market after last week's continuous fall as the
benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index gained 13.58 points to
close at 1987.95 today.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume stood at 120.75 million units, worth
299.53 million Singapore dollars (about 209.46 million U.S.
dollars). Advances overtook declines by 153 to 130 while 342 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Recently listed Chinese company Tianjin Zhong Xin was the most
actively traded stock as it registered a turnover of 27.62 million
units. It was followed by Van Der Horst which had 5.38 million
shares traded. The Development Bank of Singapore (DBS) Land was
next with 4.73 million units changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local car distributor Cycle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C), property
developer City Developments and NBT shared the top spot on the
gainers' list as each of them rose by 40 cents to finish at 14.8,
14 and 21.7 Singapore dollars respectively. The DBS Foreign and
the Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation (OCBC) Foreign gained 30
cents each to end at 18 and 14.8 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Asia Pacific, GE Life, and Gentings were the
biggest losers as each of them declined by 30 cents to close at
5.7, 15.7 and 6.9 Singapore dollars respectively. JMH 400 fell by
25 cents to end at 7.1 US dollars while Jurong Ship finished 20
cents lower at 6.2 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
