<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower Ahead of RBA Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
lower against the U.S. currency with the market being cautious
about tomorrow's Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) board meeting to
consider monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 74.58 U.S. cents, down from
Friday's close of 74.9 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia's treasury manager Paul Macarounas said
the local unit had traded well during the day in a tight range of
74.48 to 74.6 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
He said good selling earlier in the day by a local bank had
seen the Australian dollar test the 74.5 U.S.-cent level, but
buying by exporters had held it up.
</P>
<P>
"We've seen some good business here. It's hard to say whether
it's related to the end of the financial year or corporate
interest," he said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted a "tense couple of days" in the foreign exchange
markets, with dealers likely to be bearish on the local currency
until outcomes of tomorrow's RBA meeting and the U.S. Federal
Reserve's monetary policy meeting tomorrow night and Wednesday
were known.
</P>
<P>
The RBA last reduced rates by 50 basis points on May 23,
bringing its official cash rate to 5.5 percent, in line with the
comparable U.S. rate.
</P>
<P>
In Australia, the majority of financial market economists think
the RBA could ease policy by the end of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
However, Banker's Trust Australia Ltd. fixed interest
strategist Rory Robertson said it appeared increasingly likely
that the central bank would not cut rates this week.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished in Sydney at 85.27 Japanese yen,
falling from 85.49 yen on Friday and at 1.2972 Deutsche marks, up
from 1.2927.  
</P>
</TEXT>
