<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Fiscal Year at Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed the 1996-1997 financial year at a record high today as
institutions squared book positions and nervously awaited the
Reserve Bank's monthly board meeting tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market was divided as to the likelihood of a
further interest rate cut tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index jumped 23.5 points to close at 2725.9,
just shy of a record intra-day high of 2728.5 points.
</P>
<P>
Today's high on the All Ordinaries Index beats the previous
record high of 2712.6 set on June 20.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries closed the 1996/97 fiscal year 483.8 points
above its closing level for 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
Nevitts broker Stephen Mayne said investors' window dressing
for the end of the financial year underpinned the strong trading.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate sensitive banking and insurance stocks surged
amid widespread optimism that the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA)
could announce a further cut in official interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector rose 1.2 percent or 59.3 points to 4919.3
with the Commonwealth Bank jumping 26 cents to 16 Australian
dollars and its installment receipts adding 27.5 cents to 11.645
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
NAB and Westpac both rose 17 cents to 18.97 and 7.97 Australian
dollars respectively while ANZ lifted 10 cents to 9.9 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The insurance sector increased 103.7 points to 6258.6 with
National Mutual up 7 cents to 2.14 Australian dollars and HIH
Winterthur also 7 cents to 3.2 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index finished 40.7 points higher at 4301.8
while the All Resources Index was 9.8 points stronger at 1508.8.
</P>
<P>
One trader said some institutions and brokerage firms were
engaged in "window dressing" to push prices higher and inflate
their returns on paper for the year ending June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Market leader BHP leapt 33.3 cents to close at 19.483
Australian dollars after a number of announcements on its future
direction today.
</P>
<P>
BHP last week announced a net profit for the year to May of 410
million Australian dollars (307.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 7.2 points weaker at 1465.3 while in Sydney,
gold bullion was trading at 334.6 U.S. dollars an ounce from
338.15 dollars previously.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 565.74 million shares worth 970.05
million Australian dollars (727.53 million U.S. dollars) with
rises outpacing falls at 669 to 617.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
