<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Rabbi Salutes Hong Kong People's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A Jewish Rabbi saluted
patriotism of the Hong Kong people on the eve of the territory's
return to China's sovereignty at the midnight today.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Israel radio, Rabbi Levi Weiman Kelman, head of
Jerusalem's Kol Haneshama congregation who has been visiting Hong
Kong since last year, described the immediate atmosphere there as
one of "real celebration."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese in Hong Kong are by large enthusiastic about
rejoining the motherland as they described," Kelman said.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the Western media's negative reports of the Hong
Kong people's feelings about the historic return, Kelman said the
joy of the Hong Kong people over the return to the motherland
surpasses the so-called worries about their future.
</P>
<P>
"It surprised me, but the Chinese residents feel more strongly
about being connected to what they consider their natural
motherland than they do about issues of democracy and freedom of
press," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kelman added that despite the 156-years of the British
colonial rule of Hong Kong, people there still consider their
place belongs to China rather than Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish Rabbi said that there is still tremendous amount of
resentment among the Chinese residents against the British as the
colonial rulers.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the feelings among the 3,000 Jews living in Hong
Kong, Kelman said they do not worry about the future of the region
at all, adding "The Jewish community really feels unaffected by
the handover."
</P>
<P>
Shmuel Lopin, Rabbi of the Jewish community in Hong Kong, told
Israel Television Sunday that Jewish people are optimistic about
their future in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that rather than going running and hiding
ahead of the Hong Kong's return, the Jews there are growing in
number and making more money than ever.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 714 Jewish families in Hong Kong, who are mostly
not native, are traders, bankers, lawyers and others who are on
limited-time contracts with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
The radio report also said that about 300 Jewish parents and
children in Hong Kong will drift merrily tonight into the new age
of Chinese rule aboard a rented ferry at the Victoria Harbor to
share the joy of all the Chinese people celebrating the return of
Hong Kong to the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
