<HEADLINE> Manila Provides Aid to Displaced People in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
private groups are now coordinating efforts to provide assistance
to about 40,000 people who fled recent fierce conflicts in
Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Relief supplies, including food, blankets and medicine, are now
being distributed to the displaced, the Philippine News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted officials of the Social Welfare and
Development Department as saying the evacuees mainly came from the
towns of Pikit and Pagalangan in North Cotabato Province.
</P>
<P>
The evacuees are now housed in Islamic schools and temporary
evacuation centers, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said about 25 to 30 percent of the evacuees are children
and supplemental feeding and day care centers are now being set up
for them.
</P>
<P>
Government troops Sunday suspended their assaults against the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in Mindanao which started on
June 16. But the military vowed to strike again if the guerrillas
renew their terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
Intense fighting had raged since June 16 between the government
troops and MILF rebels in North Cotabato, killing more than 100
guerrillas, soldiers and civilians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
