<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas-Funded Enterprises Create More Jobs in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics show that
overseas-funded enterprises in the north China port city of
Tianjin have employed 320,000 local people, providing one-third of
the city's total job opportunities and helping to absorb employees
made redundant by state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"On top of this, Tianjin still has another 100,000 people who
are working for overseas-funded enterprises but who have not
signed contracts," said Yu Maodong, a Chinese official in charge
of labor administration.
</P>
<P>
He said that the number of employees in overseas-funded
ventures has kept increasing in recent years at a time when more
and more workers in loss-making state enterprises are being laid
off.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 overseas-funded enterprises have been set up in
Tianjin, two-thirds of which are industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city's overseas investment has reached 16
billion yuan over the past few years, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
"Overseas-funded enterprises now have become the largest
employer of people entering the work force," Yu said. 
</P>
