<HEADLINE> HK to Add Share to Kenya-China Trade: Kenyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan business official has
predicted that Hong Kong's return to China would have a more
positive influence on Kenya-China trade, The East African
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper quoted Mary Kinyani, Director of Internal
Trade at Kenya's Ministry of Commerce, as saying that the return
would further open China to Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government is confident of better quality imports
from China as there are more industries producing quality goods
in Hong Kong, which will find ready markets in East Africa, the
official noted.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya has had a good relationship with China for a long
time," he said, adding this is essential for bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of Kenya's Export Promotion Council told the paper
that "we hope to make Hong Kong a model coffee drinking city
within China" because Kenyan coffee is not yet very popular in
the city.
</P>
<P>
One sector in Kenya which could attract Hong Kong people is
likely to be tourism, the paper said, adding that local travel
agents in Hong Kong had reported growing interest in East Africa,
particularly Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Vicky Keng, Operation Manager of Morning Star Travel Service
which is one of the largest tour operators in Hong Kong, was
quoted as saying that "Kenya is currently our second choice
destination in Africa, particularly for people who have been to
South Africa before."
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the prospect of this trend spreading to
China raised exciting visions of bringing thousands of Chinese to
spend their money in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
The paper disclosed that selected Kenyan producers would visit
various Asian cities including Hong Kong next month to promote
their commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
