<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Biggest Offshore Commercial Oil Transit Base Taking Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China's biggest offshore
commercial oil transit base is taking shape at the southern tip of
the Zhoushan Islands, off the coast of east China's Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that Aoshan Petroleum Transit Station will have
an annual capacity of transferring 10 million tons of oil products
by the year 2000, according to local sources. Construction on the
site began in early 1990.
</P>
<P>
The station is owned by Sinochem-Xingzhong Oil Transit
(Zhoushan) Corporation which is jointly run by five separate
companies, including Sinochem International Petroleum Co. Ltd and
a Hong Kong company.
</P>
<P>
The site now has three berths, 22 oil storage tanks, and
computerized control systems capable of transferring 7.05 million
tons of crude oil and finished petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The station has steadily increased its handling of crude oil
and finished petroleum products, as well as in the transit volume
of them since it started operating in February 1993.
</P>
<P>
It handled 5.19 million tons of crude oil and finished
petroleum products last year, accounting for a half of Zhoushan
Port's total handling capacity. Its transit volume of crude oil
and finished petroleum products totaled 2.6 million tons in the
same year.
</P>
<P>
Workers started second-phase construction of the station in
July 1995. The work involves the building of ten 50,000-cu-m oil
storage tanks, four of which have been completed When the second
phase is completed. The station will have oil storage tanks
capable of storing 700,000 cu m of crude oil and 200,000-cu-m of
finished petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The station has also won approval from the General
Administration of Customs for the construction of new oil storage
tanks. With a combined holding capacity of 350,000 cu.m, they will
offer a bonded oil storage service to overseas customers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
