<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks' Interest Rates Likely to Slide in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's bank interest rates are
expected to come down following a drop in Treasury bills rate and
a meeting held last week between the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
and the Kenya Bankers' Association.
</P>
<P>
The CBK and commercial banks have been agreed on the measure
to encourage borrowing and stimulate economy, according to local
reports today.
</P>
<P>
The average interest rate for the 91-day Treasury bills
slipped from the 12 weeks' moving average of 20.1 percent to 18.9
percent last week. Commercial banks use the 91-day Treasury bills
rates as the benchmark for base lending rates.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates have in the past been a point of public dispute
between the CBK and government officials on one hand and
commercial banks on the other.
</P>
<P>
The governmental officials have called for reduced lending
rates in line with the steady drop of Treasury bills, continued
low rate of inflation and a stable foreign exchange regime.
</P>
<P>
The large banks, led by Barclays Bank (22 percent), charge the
lowest base interest rates while the smaller ones, led by
Investments &AMP; Mortgages Bank (31.50), charge the highest,
according to central bank figures.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates retard economic growth because only
short-term investors and existing industrialists can afford to
borrow. Few new enterprises are set up in periods of high
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Stability of the exchange rate, low inflation and high
interest rates offer attractive investment opportunities for
speculative foreign exchange inflows, making the Kenyan currency
Shilling artificially stronger than it should be, experts say.
</P>
<P>
The CBK perhaps seeks to strengthen the financial sector by
compelling poorly performing banks and this could force them to
increase their capital, they say.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia Mudavadi said in the 1997
budget speech that locally incorporated banks will be given up to
December 31, 1999, to raise their share capital from some 1.3
million U.S. Dollars to 3.6 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Only 33 out of the 52 commercial banks doing business in Kenya
have 3.6 million Dollars in capital at present.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 25 percent of Kenyan banks are below the
CBK-set industry performance standards, according to a report
recently released by the CBK's Supervision Department. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Reduces Guinea Worm Cases by 99 Percents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has reduced recorded cases
of Guinea worm from 126,400 in 1992 to 1,445 in 1996, "The New
Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
John Okidi, the field coordinator of the global 2,000/Uganda
Guinea Worm Eradication Program (UGWEP), told the newspaper that
their new target in 1997 is to prevent transmission of every
detected cases and eliminate the remaining cases.
</P>
<P>
Kampala itself reportedly has a five-year-absence of the
disease, which spreads when people drink contaminated water with
Guinea worm larva. The only exception in the city now is an
affected prisoner from Kotido District in the north-east.
</P>
<P>
UGWEP has introduced a reward system for those reporting the
disease. The remaining cases are now in the north and north-east
of the country, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
