<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 07:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's 1997 Budget Deficit Expected Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Israel's state budget deficit
for 1997 could end at 423 million U.S. dollars to 570 million
U.S. dollars, much above the target, according to a report of The
Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Leo Leiderman, head of Bank of Israel Research Department, was
quoted by the pro-government English daily as saying something
must be done to ensure that there should be no repetition of the
fiscal expansion tendency seen in the last two years of the
previous government.
</P>
<P>
He said Bank of Israel, the country's central bank, will
shortly propose to the Treasury the creation of an annual state
expenditure target to curb government spending.
</P>
<P>
At present, the government is aiming to keep the budget
deficit within its own target of 2.8 percent of the GDP, which
translates to a deficit of some 274 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this goal, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and former Finance Minister Dan Meridor agreed in May
to a budget cut by some 171 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far, the government has failed to implement the cut, with
sources close to Netanyahu admitting that he is fearful of
entering a new round of budget negotiations in the cabinet,
particularly in the light of ongoing political upheavals.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is now of the opinion that the budget deficit
will be 0.43 percent to 0.58 percent higher than the one estimated
by the government, which suggests the proposed 171 million
dollars' cut will fall short of the required cutback.
</P>
<P>
An overall economic growth will reach 2.5 percent to 3 percent
this year, but is likely to be surpassed in 1998, totalling
some 3 percent to 4 percent, according to estimates of Bank of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The bank also believes the economic slowdown is bottoming out
and does not foresee a further slowdown, or a slide into
recession. But independent economists are reportedly not as
optimistic as the official central bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
