<HEADLINE> Turkey to Upgrade Choppers Against Missile Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is to invite international
bids to equip its military helicopters with anti-missile systems
in an effort to avoid terrorist missile attacks, local newspaper
Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted defense experts, who asked not to be named, as
saying that firms from the United States, France, Sweden and
Israel would bid for equipping the Turkish helicopters.
</P>
<P>
According to expert estimate, equipping such an anti-missile
system for each helicopter will cost around 100,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 50 Sikorsky helicopters, 19 Cougars, 17 Mi-17s and
around 30 Cobras will be included in the modernization program,
defense sources said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the sources as saying that this bid is
launched to increase Turkey's military choppers' ability to resist
terrorist missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military were shocked when their two military
helicopters were downed by anti-aircraft missiles of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) rebels in northern Iraq last month,
which killed 11 servicemen.
</P>
<P>
This has forced Turkey to take urgent measures to improve its
choppers to prevent such incidents in the future.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels has been fighting a 13-year-old separatist war
in southeastern Turkey. Turkish troops began a cross-border
military operation in northern Iraq on May 14 to attack the PKK
rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
