<HEADLINE> Australia's Wool Price Expected to Continue Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Analysts today predicted that
wool prices would be weak this week after a sharp correction last
week saw the Eastern Market Indicator (EMI) plummet 47 Australian
cents to 706 cents (529 U.S. cents) per kilogram clean.
</P>
<P>
The fall followed five weeks of escalating wool prices due to
limited supply, which brought the EMI to an almost two-year high
of 753 Australian cents (564 U.S. cents) per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Brokers Wesfarmers Dalgety said today that the confidence and
strength of the market came to a halt last week in response to
increased quantities on offer, after growers released stocks
hoping to take advantage of boosted prices.
</P>
<P>
"Weakness is expected to continue this week," Wesfarmers said
in its Wool Weekly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
"However, grower reaction to the downturn is anticipated to
make this less severe."
</P>
<P>
Wesfarmers said a larger offering of 132,492 bales would be up
for sale this week in Sydney, Melbourne and Fremantle.
</P>
<P>
After this week, there will be a three-week break in sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
