<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading South African newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen
</P>
<P>
--The South Africa government is considering to buy two
floating hotels built in Ukraine and moored off the coast as
secure prisons to accommodate prisoners, spokesman for the
Department of Correctional Service said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
--The peace process in Kwazulu/Natal Province, one of the
South Africa's most volatile areas in the past decade, was on
track and would remain the responsibility of the provincial
government, except for issues of national concern, Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Star
</P>
<P>
--The Legal Aid Board of South Africa, which provides
state-funded legal representation for people who can't afford it,
has been plunged into a staffing crisis by the spiralling demand
for legal services, while almost a fifth of the board's total
staff had resigned in the past year because of the rapidly
increasing workload.
</P>
<P>
Business Day
</P>
<P>
--South Africa's small and medium-sized companies have to
seize their opportunities and use "smart strategies" to penetrate
Africa and the rest of world to explore overseas market. 
</P>
