<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lanterns, Streamers Greet Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- With just a few hours left before
the return of Hong Kong to the motherland, many places in China
have been decorated with red lanterns, colored lights and
streamers to greet the historic event.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing's Tiananmen Square, strings of giant red lanterns
have been hung high on buildings. In Shanghai, some two million
pots of flowers have been laid along the streets, and in Shenzhen,
a city neighboring Hong Kong, several hundred thousand lamps will
add color to the city's night sky.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, ordinary Chinese people are welcoming Hong
Kong's return in their own ways. In central China's Henan
Province, six brothers made the biggest drum in China for the gala
in Tiananmen Square this evening. It measures three meters in
diameter and nearly one meter in height.
</P>
<P>
Dagu Fort in Tianjin in north China, once occupied by British
invaders, has been renovated as a place for patriotic education,
and in Nanjing City in east China, where an unequal treaty was
imposed on China by imperialists, a "warning bell" weighing some
3.5 tons has been made to remind people never forget history.
</P>
<P>
Art troupes are staging various performances to greet Hong
Kong's return. Xie Jin, director of the film "Opium War," said in
an interview with Xinhua News Agency that "A nation can only face
its humiliating history when it is really standing up on its own
feet." His film is being shown in 1,300 cinemas across the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
