<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Efficiency Helps Boost Ship Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Customhouse has been
striving hard to improve its service, which has contributed much
to a marked increase in the export of ships.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the city's customs show that it supervised the
exports of ships and boats valued at 167 million U.S. dollars
between January and May of this year, an eight-fold increase on
the figure for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The shipbuilding industry has become a pillar force in China's
export of machinery and electronic commodities.
</P>
<P>
Information from China State Shipbuilding Corporation indicated
that 85 percent of ships built in China last year were exported,
earning a total of 1.19 billion U.S. dollars in foreign exchange.
Both figures are record highs.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is one of China's oldest shipbuilding bases. The port
city has several large shipyards whose competitiveness has
improved on the international market.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, half of the output value of China State Shipbuilding
Corporation was generated by Shanghai Shipbuilding Company.
</P>
<P>
Streamlining measures introduced by the Shanghai Customs
include the establishment of a new express service window at
Pujiang Customs Office to provide a swifter service to those going
through necessary export procedures.
</P>
<P>
It also provides major shipbuilders with certificates of tax
rebates for exports of vessels in time to expedite circulation of
funds. They have also accelerated inspections of imported
equipment needed for the building of exported vessels.
</P>
<P>
China-built vessels have been sold to more than 40 countries
and regions, including Norway, Greece and the United States,
themselves major shipbuilding nations. China has become the
world's third largest builder and exporter of ships after Japan
and the Republic of Korea (ROK).
</P>
<P>
According to development plans drafted for the Ninth
Five-Year-Plan period (1996-2000) by China State Shipbuilding
Corporation, China will generate 30 billion yuan in annual
shipbuilding industrial output value, build ships and boats
exceeding three million dwt annually and generate three billion
yuan in pre-tax profits by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary Confident in Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said here today that he is confident in the prosperous future
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"As we approach the midnight (of June 30), there is more
confidence in Hong Kong's future than any of us could...predict
five years ago," Cook told a press conference after a meeting with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright this morning.
</P>
<P>
"You're in a city in which the stock exchange is rising,
property prices are rising, and investment is leaping forward," he
said.
</P>
<P>
There are more people coming to Hong Kong to stay than those
leaving Hong Kong, said the foreign secretary.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the terms of the Sino-British Joint
Declaration will be adhered to, and the future for Hong Kong's
next 50 years will be as good as the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
On the deployment of Chinese troops in Hong Kong after the
handover ceremony, Cook said that under the Joint Declaration and
the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region,
China has the right to station troops within Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Declaration and the Basic Law, the
troops are for external defense only, and the internal security is
a matter of the future Hong Kong government and the Hong Kong
police, he said.
</P>
<P>
Britain wants to set up a "constructive working relationship"
with China, and central to the relationship will be Hong Kong,
which will become "a bridge, not a barrier," between the two
countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-China Trade Likely to Grow: Modi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The presence of a large number
of Indian expatriates in Hong Kong and the importance India
attaches to Hong Kong as a trade route will result in dynamic
economic cooperation between India and China, a prominent Indian
businessman said.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing Sunday before his departure for a visit to
China at the head of an Indian business delegation from July 7 to
11, k. k. Modi, vice-president of the Federation of Indian
Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FICCI), said the people of
Indian origin in Hong Kong can be the good-will ambassadors for
Indian business in China since many of them have been dealing with
India for a long time.
</P>
<P>
They can easily propagate Indian goods to China's inland and
can easily source them from India, Modi said, adding that once
this direct trade route is opened up, bilateral trade between
India and China will accelerate and can reach 1.4 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The India-China Joint Business Council (JBC) has identified a
number of projects for Chinese investment in India and China these
days are aggressively bidding for major projects in the country,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
India's investment in China has gone up over the years and a
large number of Indian companies are also exploring the
possibility of joint ventures in China, he further said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
