<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Future Britain-China Relationship Has Two pillars: Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said here today that adherance to the Joint Declaration and
a desire to build a strong and constructive relationship with
China are the two pillars of future Britain-China relationship.
</P>
<P>
He flew into here this morning to attend the handover ceremony
at midnight.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference at Kai Tak airport, Blair said: "What is
absolutely essential is that there are two pillars, foundations,
of our relationship of the future."
</P>
<P>
"The first is adherance to the Joint Declaration, the agreement
between Britain and China that guarantees the future prosperity
and freedom of Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
And secondly, a desire to build a strong and stable
relationship with China for the future, because "it is in the
interests of the people of Hong Kong, in the interests of the
people of United Kingdom, and of course, in the interests of the
people of China."
</P>
<P>
Blair voiced confidence in Hong Kong's prosperity after it
returns to China.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure that it has a good future, a prosperous future for
the people of Hong Kong provided we keep in place those basic
agreements that we have," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Later today, he will meet with Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and Premier Li Peng, shortly after attending the farewell ceremony
held by the British side at the East Tamar Site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
