<HEADLINE> Finance Bill Passed Amid Opposition Walkout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's much-debated national
budget for fiscal 1997-98 is expected to be passed today after the
Parliament passed the Finance Bill Sunday night amidst angry
walkout by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) has
called a half-day strike on July 3 in protest against the
Infrastructure Development Surcharge and some other new duties and
taxes, which they said, would undermine production.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria Sunday night piloted the
Finance Bill 1997, in which he dropped duties on a number of items
proposed in the new budget, but rejected the plea for withdrawing
the much-talked import surcharge.
</P>
<P>
Winding up general debate on the proposed budget in Parliament,
he also rejected the demand for keeping some items like slippers
and nails out of the Value Added Tax (VAT) net.
</P>
<P>
The Minister withdrew the 2.5 percent duty on raw cotton and
reduced the proposed duty of 7.5 percent on textile machinery and
textile air conditioners to 2.5 percent "considering the need of
backward linkage for readymade garments and national priority".
</P>
<P>
But Kibria spoke strongly in favor of the proposed
Infrastructure Development Surcharge and said the alternative of
such a low rate surcharge was to impose duties at a higher rate on
many more items.
</P>
<P>
The half-empty House passed the bill "unanimously" by voice
vote after the BNP legislators walked out of the House in protest
against the additional taxes.
</P>
<P>
While announcing the countrywide strike program, BNP Secretary
General Mannan Bhuiyan said the opposition in Parliament had tried
to press the government to withdraw the additional taxes but the
government did not listen to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
"Now we are compelled to go for greater movement like strike,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
