<HEADLINE> Singapore to Sign New Investment Pact with Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore and Hong Kong have
been negotiating an Investment Protection and Promotion Agreement
(IPPA) that will enhance their close bilateral economic relations,
the Business Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Even as Hong Kong prepares to become a Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China on July 1, It has been business as usual for
Hong Kong-Singapore ties, it said.
</P>
<P>
The IPPA has been under negotiation for the past year. Like
those monetary cooperation agreements that the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority signed with its regional counterparts, the IPPA with
Singapore is part of the confidence-building measures to dispel
any jitters the foreign business community might have about Hong
Kong after its return to China, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The IPPA seeks to give the investment community added
confidence in each other's territory," Chan Heng Wing, Singapore's
Consul-General to Hong Kong, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
With or without the IPPA, investment flows between the
Singapore and Hong Kong have been growing at a rapid pace, the
report noted, adding that the heavy bookings in the first-class
and business section of Singapore Airlines flights between
Singapore and Hong Kong attest to the strong commercial links.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore is expanding its enormous ties with Hong Kong
because we believe that Hong Kong will maintain its prosperity and
way of life as before. We are confident that Hong Kong will revert
smoothly from Britain to China," Chan Heng Wing said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
