<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Drivers Protest Against Gas Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nepali transporters launched a
jam-the-road campaign here Sunday to protest against the gas price
hike and demand rise in transport fares.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of buses, minibuses, tempos, taxies and other public
transportation vehicles jammed the roads in front of the Nepal Oil
Corporation (NOC) offices, with their owners calling for a 20
percent hike on fares on gas operated vehicles and 35 percent hike
on diesel operated public vehicles.
</P>
<P>
They have threatened to increase the fares unilaterally without
government permission from Monday.
</P>
<P>
On June 12, the NOC lifted the price of gas from 34 rupees (60
U.S. cents) per litre to 39 rupees (68 cents), diesel from 14
rupees (25 cents) to 17.5 rupees (30 cents) and kerosene from 9.5
rupees (17 cents) to 11 rupees (19 cents).
</P>
<P>
The NOC argued that it had no other choice because in the past
8 to 9 months, it had suffered a loss of 490 million rupees (8.5
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the price hike has since spelled a spate of protest
movements across the country.
</P>
<P>
Bowing to mounting pressure, the government decided last week
to cut the prices of diesel and kerosene by two rupees and half a
rupee respectively, but maintain the gas price unchanged at 39
rupees (68 cents) per litre.
</P>
<P>
The government said its subsidy has reached 510 million rupees
(8.95 million dollars) in the past five months alone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
