<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Foreign Ministers Meet in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen met here this morning with British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center.
</P>
<P>
Both Qian and Cook are here to attend the Sino-British Hong
Kong handover ceremony at midnight today.
</P>
<P>
Qian described the meeting as of great significance as it is
just hours before the historical moment of Hong Kong's return to
China, a moment that marks the end of a past period and ushers in
a new period.
</P>
<P>
He added that he believed Hong Kong will maintain long-term
prosperity and stability after July 1.
</P>
<P>
Cook described the coming evening as one of pride for China,
and congratulated the Chinese government on recovering Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Britain and China had made sensible and fine arrangements for
the return of Hong Kong, he said, adding that Hong Kong should
become a bridge linking the two countries in the future.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that the settlement of the Hong Kong question, which
started in 1982, took 15 years, during which there were
cooperation, disagreement and even confrontation between China and
Britain. The road was far from even.
</P>
<P>
"However, we finally found a peaceful solution to this major
problem left over by history. This is the result of both sides'
efforts to rise to the trend of the times, seek common ground
while reserving differences, and cooperate in a pragmatic manner,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that both sides should look into the future, and that
 maintaining Hong Kong's prosperity and stability is not only in
the interest of China, but also in the interest of Britain and
even the entire international community.
</P>
<P>
Cook agreed to Qian's views, and pointed out that Britain has
tremendous business interests in Hong Kong and hopes to further
develop its relations with China through Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We should continue to maintain good dialogues and contacts,
and make the Hong Kong handover a new starting point for the
Sino-British relations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers held that in the future, China and Britain
should make further efforts to develop their relations of
cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
They also exchanged views on other questions of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that Britain supports China's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The economic and trade relations between China and the rest of
the world have been developing rapidly, he said. It's a good thing
that China becomes a member of the WTO.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the wish that Britain and China could enhance
consultation and make joint efforts for the successful convening
of the Asia-Europe Meeting next year.
</P>
<P>
Qian agreed that it is conducive to world peace and stability
that Asia and Europe strengthen economic cooperation and leaders
of Asian and European countries meet regularly.
</P>
<P>
he said that Chinese and British officials can have more
contacts in this direction.
</P>
<P>
Qian invited Cook to visit China at his convenience. Cook
expressed his gratitude for the invitation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0184 </DOCNO>
