<HEADLINE> HK, ROK Sign Investment Protection Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and the Republic of
Korea (ROK) signed an investment promotion and protection
agreement here today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Denise Yue, Secretary for Trade and
Industry of Hong Kong, and Yoo Chong-Ha, Minister of Foreign
Affairs of the Republic of Korea .
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of agreement, Hong Kong and South Korea will
provide for the equal treatment of investors, compensation if
investments are expropriated, and free transfer of investments and
returns.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will also provide for the settlement of
investment disputes in accordance with internationally accepted
rules.
</P>
<P>
ROK is Hong Kong's 10th largest overseas investor. As at the
end of 1995, investment from ROK amounted to one billion U.S.
dollars, representing 1.5 percent of total overseas investment in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Correspondingly, Hong Kong is South Korea's sixth largest
source of overseas investment. Hong Kong's accumulated investment
in South Korea was 422 million HK dollars (54.1 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
This agreement is the 13th that Hong Kong has signed in the
area of investment promotion and protection. Other countries with
which Hong Kong has signed a similar agreement are the
Netherlands, Australia, Denmark, Sweden, Switzerland, New Zealand,
Italy, France, Germany, Belgium and Luxembourg, Austria and Japan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Australian PM Praises China, Blasts UK Over HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Former Australian prime minister
Bob Hawke today praised China's handling of Hong Kong's transition
and attacked Britain's role in introducing "democratic reform" to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"They (China) are acting properly in accordance with
international law, custom and practice and the provisions of the
decisions of 1984 (joint declaration)," the former minister was
quoted today by the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"The Brits grabbed Hong Kong, forcefully took it from China 150
years ago. Why? Because the Chinese had the temerity to say we are
not going to allow you to sell opium to our people," Hawke, who
was prime minister from 1983-1991, said.
</P>
<P>
"China could have taken this back ... it has chosen not to take
back Hong Kong as it was entitled to, it's chosen to honor the
99-year lease in regard to the new territories," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the so-called democratic reform introduced by Governor Chris
Patten to Hong Kong, he said "Britain had this place for 150-plus
years and they did nothing in that period about introducing
democracy until the dying minutes".
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, I am a believer in democracy, but I am not a
believer in trying to shove down other people's throats a
timetable for bringing into existence rights which took the West
an enormous period ... to bring about in our own countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"And the record of the West in regard to China is one of
barbarism, they have seized their countries, they have raped and
pillaged. The values which they have exposed to China over a
century and a half have been frightful values," Hawke said.
</P>
<P>
"And now for them to be standing up and preaching to China as
to how they should behave I find basically morally repugnant."
</P>
</TEXT>
