<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Portuguese Foreign Ministers Meet in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen met with Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime
Gama at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center here this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Both are here to attend the Sino-British Hong Kong handover
ceremony at midnight today.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers expressed their elation to be able to meet at
the historic moment of Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
Gama said that the Sino-Portuguese bilateral relations have
been developing well in recent years, and the development of the
Hong Kong-Macao relationship is also satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had had a meeting with Tung Chee Hwa, Chief
Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, and that
the relationship between Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira and
Tung is also very good.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that after July 1, 1997, Hong Kong will maintain
prosperity and stability, and the relationship between Hong Kong
and Macao will continue to develop," he added.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that the settlement of the Hong Kong question would
provide valuable experience for the Chinese and Portuguese sides
in dealing with the Macao question.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Sino-Portuguese Liaison Group has made
progress in its work which should be sped up to solve in good time
the remaining problems in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
"We will certainly achieve the smooth transition of Macao," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Gama agreed, saying that the Portuguese government is willing
to make joint efforts with the Chinese government to achieve
Macao's smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Foreign Minister Wang Yingfan was present at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who flew into Hong Kong on Sunday from Beijing for the
Hong Kong handover ceremony at midnight today, later met with
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook and U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright. He will also meet with Japanese Foreign
Minister Yukihiko Ikeda, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander
Downer, Russian Foreign Minister Y.M. Primakov and German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
