<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Improvement of Tourism Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar official paper The New
Light of Myanmar today called for improvement of tourism services
in the country to attract more number of tourist arrivals.
</P>
<P>
In its editorial today, the paper also emphasized upgrading and
development of infrastructure of tourism and availability of hotel
accommodation in cooperation with the private sector, both local
and foreign.
</P>
<P>
The paper disclosed that training courses are being conducted
in collaboration with Singapore Tourist Promotion Board and
Singapore Hotel Association Training and Education Center and
others to meet the needs in hotel management, planning, promotion
and marketing.
</P>
<P>
There are now altogether 428 hotels with 9,910 rooms available
in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also pays attention to development of hotel and tourism
in border areas. In addition to the already-built first
Thai-invested Andaman Club Resort Hotel at the Thahtay Island in
Kawthaung bordering Thailand, Myanmar has reached two more
memorandums of understanding with Singaporean and Thai investors
during the first half of this year to build more resort hotels in
Kawthaung and Tachilek.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 230,000 tourists visited
Myanmar in 1996, of which 113,169 visited Kawthaung.
</P>
<P>
The hotel and tourism sector in Myanmar had attracted 762.56
million U.S. dollars in foreign investment in 39 permitted
projects out of over 6 billion U.S. dollars' total foreign
investment by the end of May this year, ranking fourth after oil
and gas, manufacturing and real estate, the statistics added.
</P>
</TEXT>
