<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Surfers Chats About Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- "Hong Kong's return" is a popular
topic of a "virtual saloon" created on the Internet by users in
south China's Hainan Province as July 1, the red-letter-day, is
approaching.
</P>
<P>
Many local Internet users have communicated with their "network
friends" through the on-line services to hail the momentous event
with words like "proud", "happy" and "enthusiastic."
</P>
<P>
Wang Houhong, deputy governor of Hainan, has also shared his
feelings with other Internet users in the United States, Hong Kong
and the interior of China through the "virtual saloon."
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that many Internet users in Shanghai, China's
largest trade and financial city, have also held similar exchanges
through the network.  
</P>
</TEXT>
