<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - IOC President Samaranch Reaffirms HK's Post-Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Juan Antonio Samaranch,
President of the International Olympic Committee (IOC), reaffirmed
that Hong Kong will remain independent and autonomous for Olympics
and other major international competitions after it returns to
China.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch is to meet with A. de O. Sales, President of the Hong
Kong Amateur Sports Federation and Olympic Committee (HKF&AMP;OC) and
other local sports leaders for detailed discussions on related
sports issues after the handover, when Hong Kong have become a
special administrative region of China.
</P>
<P>
"For me, the most important thing is that the youth of Hong
Kong can take part in Olympic Games and all other main
international competitions in the future in an independent and
autonomous way," he said.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch made these comments upon his arrival here this
morning for ceremonies for the Hong Kong handover and the
inauguration of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) government around midnight here today.
</P>
<P>
The IOC chief is visiting Hong Kong at the invitation of the
local Sports Community for celebrations marking Hong Kong's return
to China.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law of the HKSAR, Hong Kong will in the
future keep its independent status in the field of sports under
the name "Hong Kong, China."
</P>
<P>
An official statement would be issued at the end of his visit
to Hong Kong, Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
The IOC chief is also expected to meet Tung Chee Hwa, Chief
Executive of the HKSAR, here today.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch is scheduled to leave here on Tuesday for a visit to
Beijing, where he is expected to meet Wu Shaozu, the Chinese
minister in charge the State Physical Culture and Sports
Commission, who is on a Chinese governmental delegation arriving
here later today for the handover ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch is scheduled to fly back to Hong Kong Wednesday to
attend the Reunification Cup soccer match on Thursday in Hong Kong
Stadium, where an all-star team of the International Football
Federation (FIFA) plays their counterpart from the Asian Football
Confederation (AFC).
</P>
<P>
Joao Havelange, President of the FIFA, is scheduled to arrive
here later on Monday, who is also to attend the handover
ceremonies and the Reunification Cup.
</P>
<P>
Sepp Blatter, FIFA's Secretary-general, had assured the game's
local governing body, the Hong Kong Football Association, on an
earlier visit to Hong Kong that the Association would keep its
FIFA membership as well as its independent status after the
handover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
