<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bullish Share Market Waits On Australia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market is
set to threaten its record high this week, following renewed
confidence on Wall Street and increased expectations of a cut in
official interest rates in Australia, the Sydney Morning Herald
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia board meets tomorrow and will
consider whether to deliver the fifth cut in official interest
rates in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
"Interest rate speculations is likely to resurface this week
given there is market consensus that the US Federal Reserve will
not raise rates," said Chris Loong, a fixed interest strategist.
</P>
<P>
The US Federal Reserve meets tomorrow and Wednesday. Its
decision will influence Australian markets because of "the equal
cash rates between the two economies and the vulnerability of the
Australian dollar to what happens in the US," Loong said.
</P>
<P>
Loong said there was "a high probability" that the Reserve Bank
of Australia (RBA) will move to cut rates, "as long as we have
continued stability in the Australian dollar and if upcoming
figures for retail sales and employment are on the weak side."
</P>
<P>
Ian Horton, managing director of Prudential Portfolio Managers
Australia, said continuing weak consumer demand and low inflation
meant there was not a lot to be lost from cutting interest rates:
"It doesn't seem to be a high risk move".
</P>
<P>
A key reason for RBA to cut rates is to try to boost
Australia's struggling economy, particularly the manufacturing and
retail sectors.
</P>
<P>
Australian retail trade figures and building approvals for May
are due out on Wednesday. The latter may show signs of increased
consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
RBA cut official interest rates by 0.5 percentage points just
over a month ago and opinion is divided over whether they should
implement another cut so quickly.
</P>
<P>
The Australian share market closed last week at 2702.4 points,
just 10 points below its all-time high.
</P>
<P>
"It looks like it's going to go a bit higher," Horton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
