<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of HK's Major Historical Events (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The People's Republic of China
is to resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1.
The following is a chronicle of major events in Hong Kong's
history.
</P>
<P>
From the late 1700s to 1842: in an attempt to cut trade deficit
with China, Britain started to sell opium to China from the late
1700s, thus bringing great affliction upon Chinese people and
plundering a huge amount of wealth from China. In 1838, the Qing
Dynasty government sent Lin Zexu as the imperial envoy to ban
opium trade in Guangdong. Under the pretext of China's prohibition
of opium trade, Britain decided to launch a war against China.
Hence the Opium War broke out in 1840.
</P>
<P>
On January 26, 1841: British marines disembarked near the
present Possession Street in Sheung Wan, and occupied the Hong
Kong island by force.
</P>
<P>
On August 29,1842: Britain forced the Qing Dynasty government,
which had been defeated in the First Opium War, to sign the
unequal Treaty of Nanking, in accordance with which the Hong Kong
island was ceded to Britain. The area of the island was about 78
sq. km.
</P>
<P>
In 1860: by launching the Second Opium War, Britain forced the
Qing Dynasty government to sign the Convention of Peking, which
ceded Kowloon to the British. In accordance with the convention,
the area south of the present Border Street on the Kowloon
Peninsula was ceded to Britain. The area was measured nearly eight
sq. km then.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, 1898: Britain forced the Qing Dynasty government to
sign in Beijing the Convention Respecting an Extension of the Hong
Kong Territory, and forcibly leased the area south of the Shenzhen
River and north of the Border Street, as well as 235 nearby
islands (namely, the so-called "New Territories," which account
for about 91 percent of Hong Kong's land area). The term of the
lease was 99 years and would expire in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On April 16, 1899: the British hoisted the Union Jack at Tai Po
in "New Territories", claiming that Chinese residents in "New
Territories" were under British rule from 2:50 p.m. on April 16,
1899. The local residents rose to fight the British, and were
cruelly put down by the British army with force.
</P>
<P>
On the morning of December 8, 1941: the Japanese troops started
to attack Hong Kong, and occupied it on December 25. Hong Kong was
ruled by the Japanese for three years and eight months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of HK's Major Historical Events (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On August 14, 1945: Japan announced unconditioned surrender to
the Allies. On September 16, the ceremony to accept the surrender
of the Japanese troops in Hong Kong was held in the Government
House. Britain resumed its colonial rule over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On October 1, 1949: the People's Republic of China was founded.
On January 6, 1950, Britain officially announced its recognition
of the government of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
On October 1971: China resumed its legitimate seat in the
United Nations. In March 1972, China and Britain reached an
agreement on establishing diplomatic relations at the
ambassadorial level.
</P>
<P>
On March 8: Huang Hua, the Chinese ambassador to the United
Nations, wrote the chairman of the UN Special Committee of
Twenty-Four, a committee on the decolonialization issue, declaring
that Hong Kong and Macao are not "colonies", and the solution to
the Hong Kong and Macao issues is within the scope of China's
sovereignty. In November, 1972, the UN General Assembly voted 99-5
to adopt the resolution on deleting Hong Kong and Macao from the
list of colonies.
</P>
<P>
On March 29, 1979: Deng Xiaoping, while meeting visiting
Governor of Hong Kong Sir Murray MacLehose, pointed out that Hong
Kong "is part of China's territory, but we regard Hong Kong as a
special region and a special issue to deal with. No matter how the
Hong Kong issue will be solved by 1997, the special status of Hong
Kong will be maintained, namely, within this century and over a a
long period in the next century, Hong Kong may practice its
capitalism, while we will practice our socialism." He assured
investors around the world that they did not have to worry.
</P>
<P>
On September 24, 1982: when meeting British Prime Minister
Margarite Thatcher, Deng Xiaoping made it clear that the issue of
sovereignty over Hong Kong was not open to discussion. Under
China's jurisdiction, Hong Kong's existing political and economic
systems, and even most of its laws, could be maintained.
</P>
<P>
From July 12, 1983, to September 5, 1984: China and Britain
held 22 rounds of negotiations on the issue of Hong Kong question.
On September 26, 1984, China and Britain initialed the Joint
Declaration on the Hong Kong Issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of HK's Major Historical Events (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On December 19, 1984: the Chinese and British governments
officially signed the Sino-British Joint Declaration in Beijing.
In the Declaration, the two governments solemnly announced that
the government of the People's Republic of China had decided to
resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1, 1997;
and the government of Britain would return Hong Kong to the
People's Republic of China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
On May 27, 1985: China and Britain exchanged the instruments of
ratification for the Joint Declaration and three annexes, which
demonstrated that the Joint Declaration came into force and Hong
Kong entered the transitional period.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, 1985: the Drafting Committee of the Basic Law of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region was officially
established. The committee consisted of 59 members, including 23
from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On December 18, 1985: the Consultation Committee of the Basic
Law was established in Hong Kong. It consisted of 180
representatives from all sectors and all strata of the Hong Kong
society.
</P>
<P>
On April 4, 1990: the Third Session of the Seventh National
People's Congress (NPC) deliberated and passed the Basic Law of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) and the three
annexes. The Basic Law, in the form of national law, embodies the
concept of "one country, two systems" and the principle and policy
of "one country, two systems", Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong, and a high degree of autonomy. It serves as the fundamental
code for maintenance of Hong Kong's stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
On October 7, 1992: the newly appointed Governor of Hong Kong
Christopher Patten made public the political reform bill, which
made drastic changes in Hong Kong's existing political structure.
The bill violated the Sino-British Joint Declaration, the
principle of dovetailing with the Basic Law, and the agreements
and understandings concerning the arrangements for Hong Kong's
election for 1994/1995, which were reached between the Chinese and
British governments in the late stage of drafting the Basic Law.
Hence it was called the "triple violation" bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970630.0225 </DOCNO>
