<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Philippine Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Philippine newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Manila Bulletin
</P>
<P>
-- The Commission on Election will start tomorrow a system of
continuing registration of voters that will give the opportunity
to those who had failed to enlist in the June 14, 15, 21, 22
general registration.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star
</P>
<P>
-- Defense Secretary Renato de Villa rejected Sunday a demand
by the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) for the pullout of
soldiers from captured MILF camps in central Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Daily Inquirer
</P>
<P>
-- The military Sunday called off its air, ground and river
assaults against the MILF in Mindanao, but vowed to strike again
if the guerrillas renew their terroristic activities.
</P>
<P>
Manila Standard
</P>
<P>
-- Philippine Presidential Palace and the Armed Force Sunday
debunked the accusation that the military offensive against the
MILF in central Mindanao could be a prelude to the declaration of
national emergency to justify president Ramos' continued stay in
power beyond 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
