<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Seeds in Women's Events Fall at Wimbledon Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The 1997 Wimbledon Tennis
Championships, plagued by consistent rainfalls for the last two
days, was forced to stage middle Sunday matches as six women's
seeds crashed down at the All England Club.
</P>
<P>
The fifth seed Lindsay Davenport, also the Atlanta Olympic
Champion, suffered a 7-5, 6-2 upset defeat by a Czech player
Denisa Chladkoea who ranked 57th in the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the match the American player blamed the
terrible weather in London by saying "This week was so weird. I
played on Monday and then to wait till Sunday was a real
throw-off."
</P>
<P>
25-year-old Amanda Coetzer of South Africa, the French Open
semi-finalist, also fell at the second Wimbledon hurdle after
being defeated 6-2, 6-1 by 31-year-old Canadian veteran Patricia
Boula.
</P>
<P>
The 10th-seeded Conchita Martinez, the 1994 Wimbledon champion,
was trounced by the 1.88-meter tall Helen Sukova of Czech Republic
in straight sets 6-4, 6-2. Another major upset was the downing of
the 7th-seeded German Anke Huber, who was beaten 3-6, 6-4, 6-4 by
16-year-old Russian girl Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
The other two casualties of the women's seeds are 14th-seeded
Schultz McCarthy and 16th seed Barbara Paulus of Austria who were
respectively defeated by unseeded players.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, world number one Martina Hingus, 4th seed Iva
Majoli, second seed Monica Seles, Spanish tennis star Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario and Mary Pearce of France all overcame their
opponents in Sunday's battles.
</P>
<P>
In the men's matches, the 15th seed Wayne Ferreira of South
Africa was beaten by Frenchman Cedric Poiline in straight sets 6-4
6-3 6-3. But all the other major seeds,including defending
champion Richard Krajicek and German player Michael Stich, have
cruised into the next round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
